{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930101801/0269.xml":{"full_text":"A want of the necessaries of\nlife, when the seasons have been\nfavorable, is a certain sign of\ndefect in the constitution, or of\ncriminality in the administra\nlion.\u201d\u2014Walter Savage Landor.\nVol. 19\u2014No. 267.\nMOONEYCASE HELD'JUDICIALLYNCHING\nFederal Program to\nHelp Unemployed in\nWinter Is Outlined\nBY PAUL R. MALLON.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United T\u2019ress\nWASHINGTON\u2014President Hoo\nver, declaring that \u201cas a nation we\nmust prevent hunger and cold to\nthose of our people who are in hon\nest difficulties,\u201d has announced a\nfederal program for stimulation of\nemployment during the winter\nmonths.\nThe plan provides for continua\ntion of organizations already set up,\nbut broadens their scope and ar\nranges closer co-operation of states\nand cities with the central govern\nment.\nHas Three-Fold Plan.\nA three-fold effort was outlined\nby Mr. Hoover:\n1. Co-operation with governors\nand employment organizations of\nstates and local communities.\n2. Development of employment\nmethods with national industries.\n3. Direct federal employment in\npublic works.\nA committee of five cabinet mem-\n'\"9 was named to co-ordinate the\nprogram and confer with Eugene\nMeyer, federal reserve board chair-\nPRISON RECORD\nBARES RACKET\nOF SOLICITOR\nRalph Root, 37 years old, who\nsaid he came here from Chicago,\nalmost convinced the court he was\npractically innocent when ar\nraigned today in district court.\nThen the police checked up on\nMr. Root and found that he has\nheen in prison 10 times; once for\nbigamy, twice for obtaining money\nunder false pretenses, twice for lar\nceny, twice for forgery and once\nfor white slavery.\nWhile serving a sentence in the\nfederal penitentiary at Leaven\nworth on the last named charge he\nescaped, according to the police.\nHe was sentenced to 90 days on\na chargeof vagrancy and will be\nturned over to federal authorities\nwhen released.\nHe was arrested while soliciting\nfunds for \u201ca sick man at the Y. M.\nC. A.\u201d This simple racket netted\nhim SIOO.\nWild Mother Stabs\nDaughter Fatally\nZANESVILLE. Ohio\u2014Mrs. Ruth\nTurner, 30 years old, stabbed her\n5-year old daughter, Ruth Evelyn,\nto death early today and then\nslashed her own throat. She was\nnot expected to recover. Police said\nMrs. Turner, whose husband was\naway at the time, apparetnly be\ncame suddenly insane.\nPopulation of One\n^For Maryland Town\nANNAPOLIS, Md\u2014The smallest\ntown in Maryland and possibly, in\n1\u2019 world is Arundel-on-the-Bay.\nnear here ,the complete figures for\nthe recent census disclosed yester\nday. It has one official inhabitant,\nCapt. John Wells, who is the care\ntaker for the town of 45 dwellings,\na summer resort.\nCalvin --1\nHotblister\n\u2014Says:\n\u201cAnyway us Open\nShop Gentlemen feels\nlike we have got this\nhere Ed Mitten for to\ndepend on if he should\nbeat Al Benson for\nsheriff. Because, don't\nEd appreciate our \u2018in\nnate honesty' as Her\nbie Hoover would say,\nan' didn't we indorse\nhim? Good Gawd\u2014\nain't he one of us!\"\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nman, the secretaries are Hyde, agri\nculture; Mellon, treasury; Davis,\nlabor; Lamont, commerce, and Wil\nbur, interior.\nExclude Jobless Aliens.\nThe program for the winter is\nthe most recent of a series of relief\nmeasures undertaken by the presi\ndent since the unemployment situa\ntion developed. Already favorable\nresults are being obtained from Mr.\nHoover\u2019s order to limit immigration\nto exclude aliens who have no def\ninite work promised them. The\npresident\u2019s conferences with finan\nciers and business leaders continue,\nand Mr. Hoover has kept in touch\nwith governors regarding the situ\nations in their states.\nWithout publicity, Mr. Hoover has\nbeen calling to the white house dur\ning recent weeks men who control\nor influence large business or finan\ncial interests.\nThe president had two private\nguests last night, William Z, Rip\nley, Harvard economics professor,\nand Henry M. Robinson, Los An\ngeles banker, it was announced at\nthe white house today. Both the\nbusiness and unemployment situa\ntions were discussed.\nSPEND MILLION,\nPLAN OF TOWN\nTO END SLUMP\nMUSKEGON, Mich. \u2014Spend a\nmillion this week and get business\nmoving was the campaign slogan\ntoday of six Muskegon civic clubs\nwhich were leading a drive to\n\u201cend the business depression by\nbreaking the buyers\u2019 strike.\u201d\n\u201cIt\u2019s just as important to spend\nmoney now as it w r as to buy Li\nberty bonds during the war and\nthe emergency is just as great,\u201d\nL. E. Reietdyk, who started the\n\u201cspend a million in a week\u201d idea,\nurged in his attempt to make\nMuskegon one city in which the\ngeneral business depression would\nnot be felt.\nThe entire city has joined in\nthe movement with such enthusi\nasm that the results,, are startling,\nmerchants said today, adding that\nmany customers were buying\nthings they apparently did not\n\\even need just to help get busi\nness going upward again.\nOne savings bank has added in\nterest to the drive by offering any\nresident who can get a responsible\nsigner a loan of SIOO if he will\nagree to pay it back at the rate\nof sl2 a month, $lO to be applied\non the loan and $2 to be placed\nin a savings account. More than\n100 persons had taken advantage\nof the offer today.\nFather Drives\nChildren Out;\nBlames Moon\nPeter Nanae, 32 years old, 3730\nWest Pierce st., blamed moonshine\nfor having driven his children out\ninto the cold last night, when he\nwas arraigned today in district\ncourt.\nA patrolman testified Nanae had\nchased his two small children,\nMilly, 2 years old, and Joe, 4\nyears old, who were barefooted, out\nof the home.\nHe was fined $5 on charge of be\ning drunk and disorderly.\n1,000 Gallon Still\nSeized in Illinois\nFREEPORT, Ill.\u2014Federal prohi\nbition agents today raided an alco\nhol plant with a capacity of 1,000\ngallons daily at Forreston, HL, a\nvillage near here.\nTwo Rockford men were arrested\nat the still and a large quantity of\nalcohol was seized.\nO. Edson Smith, deputy prohibi\ntion commissioner of Chicago, who\nled the raid, estimated the value of\nthe still at $25,000.\n12 DIE IN WEEK\nOF PNEUMONIA\nWith 12 deaths occurring in the\ncity from pneumonia this week,\nHealth Commissioner J. P. Koehler\nwarned against neglect of common\ncolds and influenza today.\nNinety per cent of all pneumonia\ncases are caused by neglect of colds,\nhe said.\nThe 12 deaths from this disease\nis considered high for this time of\nthe yea&\nBruening Faces Reich Vote Test\nLIFE OF RULE\nAT STAKE IN\n12 PROPOSALS\nGovernment Hopes to\nBeat All Motions\nat One Stroke.\nBY ERIC KEYSER.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nBERLIN\u2014The life of Chancellor\nHeinrich Bruening\u2019s government\nwas staked today in the reichstag.\nConvening again after a week of\nthe most stormy and hostile sessions\nin years, the reichstag considered\n12 motions of misconfidence in the\ncabinet or in the acts of individual\nministers.\nThe brown shirted Fascists, the\nNationalists and Communists an\nnounced motions of misconfidence\nin the entire cabinet. Other motions\nof misconfidence were put forward\nby the various parties, three being\naimed at Foreign Minister Dr. Jul\nius Curtis, two at Interior Minister\nDr. Joseph Wirth and two at Wil\nhelm Groener, minister of defense.\nOthers were directed against Min\nister of Agriculture Martin Schiele\nand Gottfried Treviranus, minister\nwithout portfolio.\nOutcome Is Doubtful.\nThe government hoped to defeat\nall of the inotions at one stroke by\nmoving to pass on to the next busi\nness, but the outcome was doubtful.\nIt was believed the cabinet, if it\ndefeated the motions, would ask an\nadjournment of six weeks to permit\nunfettered governmental action on\ntbe financial reform program.\nThe disorders of the last few days\nin the reichstag were renewed when\nFascists interrupted the speech of\nthe Munich states attorney, Deputy\nWilhelm Hoegner, a Socialist.\nExpel Fascist Member.\nEdmund Heines, a Fascist, ad\nvanced threateningly toward, him\nand shouted antagonizing remarks.\nThomas Esser, vice speaker, ex\npelled Heines from the reichstag for\nthe session. The Fascists shouted\ntheir protests.\nPolice revealed that a clash be\ntween Communists and Fascists in\nthe streets of north Berlin last\nnight had been more serious than\nfirst reported. Eight Communists\nwere wounded by pistol shots and\nseveral others hurt.\nBlame Idle Money\nFor Unemployment\nSPRINGFIELD, Ill.\u2014Vice Presi\ndent Charles Curtis blamed idle\nmoney for unemployment and busi\nness depression in the United\nStates in an address last night.\nSpeaking for the second time\nsihee he invaded the west tojUrge\nre-election of a Republican |ouse\nand senate, the vice president said\nthe effect of world wide trade de\npression will be overcome in this\ncountry as soon as the nation\u2019s\nmoney gets to work.\nReviewing past depressions, Vice\nPresident Curtis said practically\nall of them have occurred under\nDemocratic rule. He pointed to\nstatements of Lloyd George, Brit\nish Liberal leader, to show that the\npresent depression and unemploy\nment exist in all of Europe, except\nFrance.\nKip's Former Wife\nFined for Speeding\nNEW YORK \u2014Mrs. Alice Rhine\nlander, former Negro wife of Leon\nard Kip Rhinelander, pleaded\nguilty to a speeding charge in\nBronx traffic court yesterday and\nwas fined $23 by Magistrate Wil\nliam Farrell. She described her-\nself at 32, living in New Rochelle.\n2 MEN HURT IN\n$500,000 FIRE\nCENTRALIA, 111. Explosion of\nan oil stove in a restaurant today\nstarted a fire which damaged or de\nstroyed several store buildings, in\njured two firemen, caused damage\nof $500,000, and for a time threat\nened to spread throughout the busi\nnes district. The blaze was stopped\nwhen it reached a fireproof bank\nbuilding.\nTwo Bandits Take\nSIO,OOO From Bank\nST. LOUIS, Mo.\u2014Two bandits\nheld up the Brentwood bank, a sub\nurban institution, and escaped with\nSIO,OOO today. The men, dressed\nas bricklayers, accosted Horace\nCoon, cashier, as he arrived to open\nthe bank, forced him to let them in,\nand then ordered him to collect the\ncash for them.\nSATURDAY EVENING, OCTOBER 18, 1930.\nMother Victim of\nDry Law Tyranny\nMl\n\u25a0L IP\nT'; 1\nj\u00dfllf I\nX i\n-SI\nUntil she can wean her 8-\nmonth-old baby Mrs. Ethel Hall,\nabove, who was fined SIOO and\nsentenced to 30 days in jail, at\nGary, Ind., because her friends\ndrank their own liquor in her\nhome, will not have to start serv\ning her sentence.\nFOUR TOWNS IN\nBRAZIL TAKEN\nBY FEDERALS\nRIO DE JANEl\u00dfO\u2014Federal oc\ncupation of four towns in Minas\nGeraes state was reported today in\na communique issued by the min\nister of justice.\nThe federate, the communique\nsaid, took Muzambinho, Monte San\nto, Tronqueiras and Bom Successo,\nthe rebels making a disorderly re\ntreat.\nOccasional raids of minor char\nacter are being made by rebels in\nthe state of Espirito Santo, where\nfederal intervention has been de\nclared, the communique added, but\nany organized attempts of the revo\nlutionists have been repulsed. At\npresent, the justice ministry\u2019s offi\ncial statement said, \"perfect calm\u201d\nprevails in the state.\nAdd Federal Troops.\nSo far, 500 reservists have ar\nrived here from interior points in\nthe state of Rio de Janeiro, in an\nswer to the mobilization call, it was\nannounced.\nA presidential decree issued to\nday authorized the Bank of Brazil\nto issue 300,000 contos (approxi\nmately $33,000,000) paper currency\nwhich will be guaranteed by 1,000,-\n000 pounds sterling (about $5,000,-\n000) and the remainder in govern\nment bonds.\nThe decree declares the present\n\u201cextreme necessity justifies\u201d the\nemergency issue of the notes.\nRebels Claim Victory'.\nRIO GRANDE DU SUL, Brazil-\nFurther victories were claimed to\nday by the revolutionary army. A\nbulletin issued at rebel headquarters\nhere claimed that revolutionary\nforces occupied the city of Christa\nlina, in the state of Goyaz, and that\nthe federal garrison at Sao Joao\nDel Rei was captured with its entire\ncomplement of officers and some\n400 soldiers.\nFederal Post Stronger.\nITARARE, SAO PAULO-PAR\nANA FRONTIER\u2014Having repelled\none rebel attack, federal forces\nstrengthened their position south of\nHarare today in anticipation of fur\nther assaults.\nWOMAN IS HELD\nON DRY CHARGE\nMrs. Francis Budnik. 1026 North\nMilwaukee st., who was arrested by\nfederal prohibition agents late yes\nterday, waived preliminary hearing\nbefore Floyd E. Jenkins. United\nStates court commissioner today,\nand was bound over to the federal\ngrand jury under a bond of SSOO.\nAgents who raided her rooming\nhouse and grocery store yesterday,\nseized 12 gallons of wine.\nFind Automobile of\nMachine Gun Killers\nKILLED WIFE\nOFGAMDLERIN\nKIDNAP PLOT\nNew Lingle Clue Is\nSeen in Peoria\nSlaying.\nPEORIA, 111. The richly fur\nnished limousine from which three\ngangsters escaped after wounding\nClyde Garrison, wealthy gambler\nand killing his wife, Cora, was\nfound abandoned near here today.\nBlood on the velour upholstery\nand floor rug revealed that at least\none of the assassins was wounded\nwhen Garrison fired at them. A box\nof machine gun cartridges, a ma\nchine gun clip and a man\u2019s kid\nglove from the left hand were found\nin the automobile.\nThe limousine also contained two\ndog leashes, a roll of three-inch ad\nhesive tape and three new padlocks\nwith keys attached. All of this\nequipment, it was pointed out, could\nbe used by kidnapers to prevent\ntheir victims from escaping.\nLingle Case Clue?\nPolice believed the men who shot\nthe gambler and his wife were \"Chi\ncago gangsters. They recalled that\nAlfred J. Lingle, Chicago Tribune\nreporter, was shot by a left-handed\nkiller and pointed out that the glove\nfound in the automobile might have\nbeen discarded by the man who\nfired on Garrison, so he might bet\nter manipulate the machine gun.\nThe automobile license plates\nwere traced and it was discovered\nthe car was stolen four months ago\nfrom Austin D. Steffner of Chicago.\nHis right leg shattered by four\nsub-machine gun bullets, Garrison\ndeclared today from a hospital cot\nthat he felt certain the men who\nkilled his wife were gangsters from\nChicago or St. Louis and that he\nwas positive he wounded one of\nthem.\nKnown to Police.\nPolice also expressed belief in the\nkidnaping theory and cited as proof\nTurn to Page Two, Column One.\nFour Injured as\nHeater Explodes\nCHICAGO\u2014Four persons were\ninjured today when a water .heater\nexploded in a restaurant.\nEugene Vankuski, 34 years old,\ncook, and Peter Conelly, policeman\nwere injured seriously and were\ntaken to a hospital.\nAgnes 3alovik, 40 years old, dish\nwasher, and Terry Lawrow, 17\nyears old, son of one of the owners\nof the restaurant were burned and\nbruised.\nMarried 21 Years,\nGets New License\nHiram Lewis Baxter, 45 years old,\na woodworker, 922 Clybourn st.,\ncelebrated the 21st anniversary of\nhis marriage to Mrs. Bertha Bax\nter, today, by taking out a marriage\nlicense to wed Mrs. Viola Sawyer,\n39 years old, 528 Wells st., a cigar\nmaker. Hiram was divorced from\nBetrha in 1926. Mrs. Sawyer has\nbeen married twice before.\n2 TRY HOLD-UP;\nBOTH CAPTURED\nCINCINNATI, Ohio Two men\nwere captured here today shortly\nafter attempting to hold up W. C.\nZeperlin, treasurer of the Mills\nRestaurant Co., and steal a $5,200\npayroll.\nThough menaced by a shotgun\nand a revolver in the hands of the\nrobbers, Zeperlin stepped on a\nburglar alarm and summoned po\nlice. The bandits, becoming fright\nened, abandoned their project and\nfled.\nOne of them, still carrying a shot\ngun, was captured in the Dixie\nTerminal building a block away.\nThe other was captured in the\nbuilding housing the Mills offices.\nTwo bandits kidnaped Davis\nLevy, president and treasurer of the\nG. and S. Manufacturing Co., as he\nleft a suburban bank here today\nand robbed him of a $2,179 pay\nroll.\nEntered ae second-class matter August 25, 1920. at the postoffice BQ T P T IT? P F CFMT^\nat Milwaukee. Wisconsin, under the Act of March. 3, 1879. A avA\\w<A> 1 A AIXA-zA-i sA O\nBeautiful Greek\nSecond in Test\nJl\u00a7\n^f-gnljl^ilO^\nThis lovely girl is Miss Alice\nDiplaracos of Athens, Greece,\nwinner of the second prize in the\ninternational beauty contest in\nRio de Janeiro. The photograph\nwas taken on her arrival in New\nYork. Miss Diplaracos is 18 years\nold, speaks five languages and\ndeclares she has no talking pic\nture aspirations.\nEXMILWAUKEE\nMAN MURDERED\nIN NEW YORK\nAbraham Greenblatt, 20 years old,\nsaid to be a former Milwaukeean\nwho died in New York, is believed\nto have been murdered, local police\nwere informed today.\nGreenblatt w r as at first thought to\nhave died from natural causes.\nIt was learned, however, that\nthere was bullet hole in his right\nlung. Greenblatt is not known to\nMilwaukee police.\nOPEN DRIVE ON\nABORTION MILLS\nReports that three women were\nseriously ill in Milwaukee hospitals\ntoday after undergoing illegal op\nerations, spurred on the district at\ntorney\u2019s office in an effort to clean\nup the abortion mills in the city.\nTwo women were admitted to the\ncounty hospital, Wauwatosa, suffer\ning serious illness as the result of\nthe operations. Another was\nbrought to a south side hospital.\nEfforts are being made by the\ndistrict attorney\u2019s office to discover\nthe persons responsible for the con\ndition of the women.\nIn one case, a victim who was\nquestioned at the hospital, refused\nto give officials any information,\nsaying she was willing \u201cto carry\nher secret to the rave.\u201d\nVIADUCT DELAY\nLAID TO ROAD\nDelay in the repairing of the\nSixth st. viaduct, was charged to\nthe North Shore line by Manuel\nCutler, superintendent of buildings\nand bridges, today.\nCutler declared that the work is\nbeing held up unnecessarily by the\nNorth Shore\u2019s slowness in replacing\ntracks on the viaduct.\nA 'conference between North\nShore officials and representatives\nfor the city will be held next week\nto determine if the work cannot be\nexpedited.\nSNOW FLURRIES\nPROVIDE FIRST\nWINTER TASTE\nTemperature May\nStrike New Low\nfor Fall.\nMilwaukee experienced its first\ntaste of winter today with the mer\ncury dropping to 28 degrees and\nsnow flurries, accompanied by pen\netrating northwest winds which\nwill continue over the week-end,\naccording to a forecast made to\nday by Frank W. Coleman, weather\nobserver.\nAt noon today the temperature\nhad risen to 33 degrees, but will\nfall again before night, Coleman\nsaid, with the lowest record of the\nseason established before tomor\nrow.\nThe Milwaukee temperature at\n4 a. m. today was only four de\ngrees higher than that reported in\nthe lowest parts of the state. It\nwas 24 degrees at Superior.\nStorm warnings were hoisted at\n9 a. m. today, when Coleman pre\ndicted that the winds would reach\na gale velocity over the lake.\nFive Die in Canada.\nCHICAGO \u2014An autumnal storm\nthat swept over Canada with mid\nwinter intensity, killing at least five\npersons and bringing traffic to a\nstandstill in many sections, spread\ntoday over almost the entire north\nern half of the United States and\nextended its chilling grip even into\nthe usually sunny southland.\nAppeal Rejected,\nConvicted Pair\nAmong Missing\nDeputies of the United States\nmarshal\u2019s office late today were\nstill seeking John F. L. O\u2019Leary\nand Henry J. Sullivan, lawyers,\nwhose appeal for new trial yester\nday was refused by the circuit court\nof appeals, Chicago.\nThe attorneys have enjoyed nine\nmonths of freedom since their con\nviction in federal court here of con\nspiracy to violate the veteran\u2019s com\npensation act.\nThey have tried to evade their\nsentences of one year in the house\nof correction and the fine of SSOO\nimposed upon them by Judge F. A.\nGeiger for manipulating the $2,461\nclaim for an ex-service man and\nsharing in the proceeds.\nHILL FALLS ON\nAUSTRALIAN HOP\nMELBOURNE, Australia\u2014Flight\nLieut. C. W. Hill, who is attempt\ning to break Bert Hinkler\u2019s Eng\nland-to-Australia flight record of\n15 days, 12 hours, crashed between\nKoepang and Atamboea, on the is\nland of Timor, Dutch East Indies,\naccording to word received here to\nnight.\nThe flier was uninjured, but his\nplane was damaged. No details\nwere received.\nMeanwhile, it was reported that\nCom mander Charles Kingsford-\nSmith, who left Croyden several\ndays after Hill\u2019s departure, was re\nported approaching Port Darwin,\nthe first stopping point in Australia.\nPlane Kills Woman in Boat.\nPENSACOLA, Fla.\u2014Careful in\nspection of more than 50 seaplanes\nwas made at the naval air station\nhere in an effort to throw some light\nupon the killing here late yesterday\nof Mrs. Allen Lee Edgecomb, mother\nof five children, and serious injury\nof Alfred G. Simmons, her fishing\ncompanion. They were struck by\nan unidentified plane as they fished\nfrom a boat in the bay. Mrs. Edge\ncomb was killed when her head was\nstruck by the plane\u2019s propeller.\nBuck Hops for Newark.\nCOLUMBUS, Ohio\u2014Robert Buck,\n17-year-old New Jersey high school\nflier attempting to set a new junior\nwest-east transcontinental recon],\nleft Port Columbus at 9:52 a. m.\ntoday for Newark, N. J. His elapsed\ntime, since leaving Los Angeles, was\n20 hours and 12 minutes. A short\ntime before buck hopped off Miss\nLaura Ingalls of New York, at\ntempting a new west-east record\nfor women, also took off for the\neast. Both landed here late yester\nday.\nHOME\nEDITION\n25 EDITORS AT\nMEETING URGE\nHOOVER ACTION\nRequest Crime Board\nBe Given Evidence\nfor Probe.\nFRENCH LICK SPRINGS'\u2014\nPresident Hoover today was called\nupon by the 25 Scripps-Howard\nnewpapers representatives assem\nbled at their biennial editorial con\nference here to intervene in the\nMooney-Billings case.\nCharacterizing as \u201cjudicial lynch\ning\u201d the course of California courts\nthus far in connection with the\ncase, the editors wired the presi\ndent a resolution asking that the\ncelebrated case be placed before the\nWickersham crime Investigating\ncommission for review and possible\npublic action.\nPledge Constant Pubilicity.\nThe resolution was inspired by\nnews dispatches from San Francis\nco stating there was a definite pos\nsibility of prolonged delay In the\nreport of the California supreme\ncourt on the recently heard pardon\nappeal of Warren K. Billings and\nThomas J. Mooney.\nThe resolution pledged the editor\u00ae\nto keep ^the details of the case be\nfore the public until \u201cpublic con\nfidence in the courts is restored.\u201d\nThe editors declared the present\neconomic depression presented a\ntemporary but real national crisis\ncomparable to a war emergency and\npledged themselves to initiate and\nsupport in relief and employment\nmeasures.\nFavor Dry Repeal.\nA study of the economic situation\nwas indorsed with recognition of\nthe problem of a shorter working\nweek and working day and of the\nfundamental necessity of insuring\nto wage-earners continuity of em\nployment.\nIn the field of prohibition, the ed\nitors passed a resolution indorsing\nthe early repeal of the 18th amend\nment and declared that In their\njudgment a new answer to the\nproblem of liquor control must be\nsought by returning the control Into\nthe hands of the states.\n3 Students Die\nIn Auto Crash on\nWay to Navy Game\nFREDERICKSBURG, Va.\u2014Three\nuniversity students were killed early\ntoday in an automobile accident\nwhile on their way to the Navy-\nDuke football game at Annapolis,\nMd.\nThe dead were Fred Ingram,\nHigh Point, N. C., a student at\nNorth Carolina State, Raleigh;\nJames Johnson, Trenton, N. J., and\nHenry Chapman, Hagerstown, Md.\nJohnson and Chapman were stu\ndents at Duke university.\nThomas Miller, Baltimore, and\nJames Jarrett, Tomasville, N. C.,\nboth Duke students, were injured\nand are in a critical condition at\nFredericksburg hospital.\nThe roadster in which the five\nstudents were traveling collided\nwith a moving van near Thornsburg,\n14 miles south of here.\nStudent Killed, 3 Hurt.\nSOUTH BEND, Ind.\u2014Robert P.\nDriscoll, Ithaca, N. Y., a senior at\nNotre Dame university, was killed\nand three other students were in\njured last night when their auto\nmobile collided with another driven\nby Frank Justus of Grand Rapids,\nMich.\nJustus\u2019 shoulder was fractured.\nThe other students, .11 of whom suf\nfered minor injuries, were James\nW. Murray, Batavia, N. Y., Thomas\nF. Dunn. Pittsburgh, and William\nF. Walsh, Montclair, N. J.\nFINE GAMBLING\nOPERATORSIOO\nSteve Pizur, 462 Tenth st., was\nfined SIOO today in district court on\na charge of conducting a gambling\nhouse. Nine inmates were each\nfined $5.\nIVeather\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Partly cloudy\nand continued cold tonight and tomor\nrow. Strong west to northwest winds.\nWisconsin: Cloudy tonight; tomorrow\ngenerally fair; continued cold.\nTEMPERATURES.\n1 a. m 301 7 a. m. 29\n2 a. m 80 8 a. m. 30\n3 a. m 29l 9 a. 31\n4 a. m 28'10 a. m ...31\n5 a. m 28111 a. 32\n6 a. m. 28\u2019Noon 33\nHumidity: 7 p. m., 54; 7 a. m., 64;\nnoon, 71.\nTemperature- 24 hours to midnight:\nMaximum, 41; minimum, 32; mean, 36;\nnormal. 51. Midnight to 10 a. m.: Max\nimum. 31; minimum, 28; relative humid\nity, 64; wind velocity at 7 a. m., 18\nmiles; direction of wind at 7 a. m\u201e west;\nsunrise today, 6:09; sunset, 5:05.","height":"28761","width":"21180"}}
